,"1130–Female":"1130–preminula","1155–Female":"1155–preminula","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1125":"1125","after 1183":"nakon 1183.","1155":"1155","about 1125":"oko 1125.","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","about 1155":"oko 1155.","Italy":"Italija"},"cs":{"about 1125–after 1183":"okolo 1125–po 1183","1130–Female":"1130–Zesnulá","1155–Female":"1155–Zesnulá","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1125":"1125","after 1183":"po 1183","1155":"1155","about 1125":"okolo 1125","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","about 1155":"okolo 1155","Italy":"Itálie"},"da":{"about 1125–after 1183":"omkring 1125–efter 1183","1130–Female":"1130–Afdød","1155–Female":"1155–Afdød","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1125":"1125","after 1183":"efter 1183","1155":"1155","about 1125":"omkring 1125","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","about 1155":"omkring 1155","Italy":"Italien"},"nl":{"about 1125–after 1183":"circa 1125–na 1183","1130–Female":"1130–Overleden","1155–Female":"1155–Overleden","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1125":"1125","after 1183":"na 1183","1155":"1155","about 1125":"circa 1125","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","about 1155":"circa 1155","Italy":"Italië"},"en":{"about 1125–after 1183":"about 1125–after 1183","1130–Female":"1130–Deceased","1155–Female":"1155–Deceased","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1125":"1125","after 1183":"after 1183","1155":"1155","about 1125":"about 1125","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","about 1155":"about 1155","Italy":"Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"di","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 狄, a term referring to the tribes in ancient northern China: (i) from Di (狄), the name of an ancient state (thought to have been located in Hebei or Shandong province), which was granted to Xiao Bo or Kao Bo by King Cheng of Zhou (reigned 1042–1021  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Ku Di (庫狄) family during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) traced back to other minority ethnic groups in ancient northwestern China.","Mandarin form of the Chinese surname 邸, meaning ‘official residence’ in Chinese: (i) from placename Di (邸), the name of a county (unidentified location). (ii) said to be borne by some descendants of Kujula Kadphises (called 丘就郤 or 邸就郤 in Chinese, 30–<i>c.</i> 80  AD ), founder of the Kushan Empire (one branch of the Yuezhi people originating from western China) located in Central Asia during the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Chi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Dong, Yun, Cheng, Jae, Yong, Cheng Chung, Chi, Chun, Duk, Fang, Feng.  Korean Chung, Chong, Jae Hong, Moon, Myong, Pong, Shen, Yoo, Byung, Chang, Chol, Chong Hun.  Southeast Asian Phi, Hung, Ly, Tu, Denh, Do Van, Duong, Hao, Kieu, Mui, Nga, Phat.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 池, meaning ‘moat’ in ancient Chinese: (i) acquired as a surname by people who lived beside a moat. (ii) from Chi (池), said to be the name of an ancient state (of unknown location and period). (iii) from the personal name Chi (池), personal name of a son of an official in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 遲, meaning ‘late’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of Chi Ren (遲任), a person who lived during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the Chinese compound surname Yu-Chi (尉遲), originally the name of a tribe from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iii) from the second element of the personal name Zi Chi (子遲), style name of Fan Xu, a student of Confucius (551–479  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Pietro","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Piero","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Pietro di Palearia was born about 1125, in Italy. He had at least 1 daughter with Letitia di Manoppello. He died after 1183."},"et":{"about 1125–after 1183":"umbes 1125–pärast 1183","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1125":"1125","after 1183":"pärast 1183","1155":"1155","about 1125":"umbes 1125","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","about 1155":"umbes 1155","Italy":"Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1125–after 1183":"noin 1125–1183 jälkeen","1130–Female":"1130–Kuollut","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","1125–1183":"1125–1183","1125":"1125","after 1183":"1183 jälkeen","1155":"1155","about 1125":"noin 1125","1130":"11